{% extends "documentation/reference/component" %}

{% block componentDetails %}
	<p>
		The <code>extends</code> tag is used to declare a parent template. It should be the
		very first tag used in a child template and a child template can only extend up to one 
		parent template.
	</p>
		
	<p>
		The best way to understand template inheritance is to study an example. Let us look
		at a parent template called "base.peb":
		<pre><code>{{ '
<html>
	<head>
		<title>{% block title %} {% endblock %}</title>
	</head>
	<body>
		<div id="content">
			{% block content %} 
				Default content goes here.
			{% endblock %}
		</div>
		
		<div id="footer">
			{% block footer %}
				Default footer content
			{% endblock %}
		</div>
	</body>
</html>
' | trim | escape }}</code></pre>
	</p>
	
	<p>
		And now let's look at "home.peb" which extends "base.peb":
		<pre><code>{{ '
{% extends "base" %}

{% block title %} Home {% endblock %}

{% block content %}
	Home page content.
{% endblock %}

' | trim | escape }}</code></pre>
	</p>
	
	<p>
		And finally let's look at the resulting output of rendering "home.peb":
		<pre><code>{{ '
<html>
	<head>
		<title> Home </title>
	</head>
	<body>
		<div id="content">
			Home page content will override the default content.
		</div>
		
		<div id="footer">
			Default footer content
		</div>
	</body>
</html>

' | trim | escape }}</code></pre>
	</p>

	<p>
		To summarize, parent templates define blocks and child templates will override
		the contents of those blocks. If a child template does not override the content
		of a particular block, the content provided by the parent template will be used.
	</p>
	<p>
		A child template is <strong>only</strong> used to 
		override the contents of parent blocks and therefore it should not have any
		content sitting outside of <code><a href="block">block</a></code> tags; that content
		will be ignored. 
	</p>
	
	<p>
		There is no limit to how long of an inheritance chain that you can create; i.e. a child
		template can itself have a child template. A lot of potential comes from this fact because
		you can create a hierarchy of templates to minimize how much content you have to write on the lower levels.
		Here is a fictional inheritance tree to show how a news website might organize their templates:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li>base (contains structural HTML)
			<ul>
				<li>home</li>
				<li>article
					<ul>
						<li>news</li>
						<li>opinion</li>
						<li>entertainment</li>
						<li>technology</li>
					</ul>
				</li>
				<li>contact us</li>
			</ul>
		</li>
	</ul>
	
{% endblock componentDetails %}
	